2500|$|In early 2003 he was {{reported}} {{to be one of the}} cabinet's chief opponents of military <b>action</b> <b>against</b> <b>Iraq,</b> and on 17 March he resigned from the Cabinet. In a statement giving his reasons for resigning he said, [...] "I can't accept collective responsibility for the decision to commit Britain now to military action in Iraq without international agreement or domestic support." [...] He also praised Blair's [...] "heroic efforts" [...] in pushing for the so-called second resolution regarding the Iraq disarmament crisis, but lamented [...] "The reality is that Britain is being asked to embark on a war without agreement in any of the international bodies of which we are a leading partner—not NATO, not the European Union and, now, not the Security Council". Cook's resignation speech in the House of Commons received an unprecedented standing ovation by fellow MPs, was described by the BBC's Andrew Marr as [...] "without doubt one of the most effective, brilliant resignation speeches in modern British politics." [...] Most unusually for the British parliament, Cook's speech was met with growing applause from all sides of the House and from the public gallery. According to The Economists obituary, that was the first speech ever to receive a standing ovation in the history of the House.|$|E
